Data Science Tutorial - Heart Disease¶

Tutorial by Luke Perry¶

Motivation¶

Heart disease causes 1 in every 4 deaths according to the cdc. My grand father recently had a heart attack. Now, my family and I are now all considered "predisposed" and at risk to have heart attacks too. Predicting if someone is at risk for heart disease can start the process of early intervention, and possibly avoid a heart attack or another heart related emergency.

Tutorial Description¶

This tutorial will focus on predicting heart disease using modern data science approaches taught in UMD's CMSC320 but are industry standard practices. We will be utilizing modern data science tools to iterate through "The Data Science Pipeline" as outlined in UMD CMCS320. The Data Science Pipeline has 5 stages, and they are data collection, management/representation, exploratory analysis, hypothesis testing/machine learning, and lastly summarizing our insights attained.

Prerequisites¶

This tutorial assumes the reader has beginner to intermediate knowledge of Python programming, Jupyter Notebooks, and statistics.

The tools required for this tutorial are Python and Jupyter Notebook. The reader will also need to install the following modules:

  1. numpy (follow up article at link)
  2. pandas (follow up article at link)
  3. matplotlib (follow up article at link)
  4. seaborn (follow up article at link)
  5. statsmodels (follow up article at link)
  6. sklearn (follow up article at link)

Part 1: Data Collection¶

1.1 Collecting Data¶

Typically the first step to the data science pipeline is collecting data (follow up article at link). The hyperlink leads to an article about scraping data if you're interested in learning more. In the real world, data is never uniform and clean. A lot of data science is just parsing and collecting data. We were lucky enough to find a good dataset, as documented below, but often you'll need to spend a decent chunk of time collecting, parsing, and cleaning data. We will be using a pre-prepared dataset from Kaggle (follow up article at link), the self proclaimed "world's largest data science community".

We'll be using a build in pandas function that ingests csv files for us from URLs

1.2 Pandas¶

pandas (follow up article at link) is a modern datascience tool for manipulating and analyzing data. Pandas is built on the concept of a "Dataframe" which is an object in pandas for data manipulation similar to a table. Pandas has a lot of very convenient native features such as slicing, graphing, merging, and is optomized for performance. Pandas is very popular among the datascience community. First, we need to collect our data before we can do anything else.

Another popular alternative is working with/from databases, but Pandas makes it very easy to work with data in Python, and is the "industry standard" however it is limited by the amount of memory on your machine. We aren't working with a large dataset so this isn't a problem. But with larger datasets other tools like databases may have to be used.

Part 2: Data Management/Representation¶

2.1 Prerequisite Domain Knowledge Defintions¶

  1. Ventricle): One of two chambers at the bottom of the heart responsible for pumping blood in and out of the heart (follow up article at link)
  2. Angina: A condition marked by severe pain in the chest, often also spreading to the shoulders, arms, and neck, caused by an inadequate blood supply to the heart. (follow up article at link)
  3. Asymptomatic: Showing no symptoms (follow up article at link)
  4. Electrocardiogram: An Electrocardiogram (ECG) is a simple and fast test used to evalaute the heart. Electrodes are placed on the chest, arms, and legs. Then, the electrical activity of the heart is recorded, measured, interpreted, and printed out. (follow up article at link)
  5. ST Segment: The isoelectric period measured on an ECG when the ventricles are in between depolarization and repolarization. During exercise, a normal segment slopes downwards or is flat. A person with heart disease's segment will slope sharply upwards during exercise. (follow up article at link)
  6. ST Depression: An ST segment measured on an ECG that is abnormally below the baseline (follow up article at link)

2.2 Dataset Labeling Issues¶

The dataset on Kaggle actually didn't include a description of every feature, 6 of the features in the dataframe had missing information.

Sometimes, when you have an inaccurate data descriptions you can backtrack to the datasets source and try to reverse engineer the descriptions. Unfortunately, this data set did not include their source.

The next option is to try and gather domain knowledge on the topic through research, then try to decipher what the dataset labels and values mean.

However, we were lucky and found a comment on Kaggle that included someone who already did the domain knowledge research for us and decoded the data labels.

2.3 Dataset Labels¶

  1. Age: Age of the patient
  1. Sex: Sex of the patient (1 = male; 0 = female)
  1. cp: Chest Pain type chest pain type
    • 1 = typical angina
    • 2 = atypical angina
    • 3 = non-anginal pain
    • 0 = asymptomatic
  1. trtbps: resting blood pressure (in mm Hg)
  1. chol: cholesterol in mg/dl fetched via BMI sensor
  1. fbs: fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl (1 = true; 0 = false)
  1. restecg: resting electrocardiographic results (1 = normal; 2 = having ST-T wave abnormality; 0 = hypertrophy)
  1. thalach: maximum heart rate achieved
  1. exng: exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)
  1. oldpeak: ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest
  1. slp: the slope of the peak exercise ST segment (2 = upsloping; 1 = flat; 0 = downsloping)
  1. caa: number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy
  1. thal: condition of arteries 0 = null; 1 = fixed defect; 2 = normal; 3 = reversable defect
  1. output: diagnosis of heart disease, based on angiographic imaging (0 = <50% diameter narrowing; 0 = >50% diameter narrowing)

Part 3: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Data scientists need to explore data (follow up article at link) before proceeding with trying to explain. The rationale behind this is intuitive, you could never explain that which you do not understand. So first, the data scientist tries to understand the data by exploring it, then begins to try and explain the data with machine learning or statistical methods like hypothesis testing.

3.1 Verifying Data¶

The first step to exploring data, is verifying the values in the data. There are many ways to approach this, we lucked out that our dataset is already quite clean, so all we need to do is make sure that our analysis won't be affected by mislabeled data, data improperly parsed by pandas, and N/A values.

3.1.1 Step by Step Code Walk-Through¶

  1. Verify the data labels that are encoded contain the correct values (if sex is 0 or 1, make sure sex only contains a 0 or 1)
  1. Verify the types of data in the dataframe is correct (if the value is a number, make sure it is not labeled as a date)
  1. Verify there are no N/A values in the dataset

3.3 Correlation Matrix¶

A common way data scientists like to explore data, is to figure out what parameters are related to other parameters. A great way to visualize relationships between variables quickly is with a correlation matrix. There are many ways to visualize correlations, such as R-squared values, but a correlation matrix is a great quick high level approach. Here's an article that goes more in depth about correlation and dependence (follow up article at link) and here's an article specifically about the correlation function (follow up article at link) we'll be using in pandas

If we know what variables are the most likely to influence being at for being diagnosed with heart disease, then we know these are the variable we should use to predict if someone is at risk for being diagnosed with heart disease. We can then use these variables as parameters for our machine learning later in the tutorial

A value of 1 in a correlation matrix means a variable is perfectly correlated, a zero means a value is not correlated at all, and a negative number means there is an inverse correlation.

3.3.1. Step by Step Code-Walkthrough¶

We can use panda's build in correlation function (follow up article at link) to achieve this, and is hyperlinked to the pandas documentation for you to learn more about it. Then, we'll plot this correlation with seaborn. We also wrote a quick line of code to expand seaborn's plot using pylot, so the tiny values are a little easier for us to read.

3.3.2 Insights¶

We can see from this correlation matrix, that the dependent variable "output" (risk of heart disease) is strongly correlated with cp (chest pain), thalachh (maximum heart rate), slp (ST segment slope during peak exercise) are all strongly correlated with heart disease.

This make sense, we would expect someone's physiological (follow up article at link) measurements to be strongly correlated with heart disease. You would think someone experiencing chest pain would be prone for heart disease, that is self-explanatory. You would also expect someone with a high heart rate to also be prone to heart disease, because their heart is working overtime and will wear itself out. Additionally, something that is intuitive but only after reading the prerequisite domain knowledge definitions in section 2.1, is that the ST segment during exercise is also correlated.

What is surprising to see here, is that cholesterol isn't highly correlated with heart disease. My gut reaction is that age should be too, however I suppose we can justify age not being correlated with heart disease by recognizing there are both very unhealthy and unhealthy people across all the spectrums of age.

3.4 Violin Plots¶

Distribution of data is extremely important, it gives us a great insight into what an "average" value in the dataset might be, and it might help us start to formalize hypotheses about why the data is distrbuted the way that it it is.

A great tool for visualizing distributions of data is violin plots (follow up article at link). There are many ways to visualize data distrbutions, but violin plots are nice because they are very easy to read, and quite easy to code up with matplotlib and seaborn.

Let's take the time to visualize some of the variables that showed up high in the correlation matrix. The dependent variables Cp (chest pain) and thalachh (resting heart rate) both appear to be strongly correlated with heart disease. I also just intuitively think that age and sex will be as well, despite the correlation matrix stating otherwise. Let's draw violin plots for these variables.

Note: Violin plots in Seaborn VS Matplotlib¶

Violin plots (follow up article at link) functions are available in both seaborn and matplotlib. I chose matplotlib for this section because I did not like how seaborn's violin plots show their distribution violins beyond actual min and max values in the distribution. The inside of the violin, the box and whisker, is the actual value but the violins that sometimes go above and beyond the max values are not very intuitive. I think they're hard to read. For example, when a seaborn violin plot's violin shows that resting heart rates below 0, that is quite confusing. You had to look at the boxplot inside the actual violin to understand the graph. I thought this was extremely counter intuitive, and decided to go with matplotlib for this part of the tutorial.

3.4.1 Step by Step Code Walk-through¶

Matplotlib isn't as nice as seaborn, matplotlib was a library wrote in the 90s and is quite dated. So, matplotlib violin plots (follow up article at link) require a little bit of heavier lifting on the user's part, compared to the nicer one-liner seaborn violin plot (follow up article at link) functions. However, never fret, we got this!

  1. We need to group the values we want to plot. Violin plots shine when they can be used for grouped data. The easiest way to group data is to use a dictionary and separate values based on whatever group we want on the x-axis.
  2. Once we have the points separated, we just call matplotlib's violinplot() function and pass in the data from our dictionary, along with the associated position array for the plots
  3. Lastly, we clean up the plot by adjusting the x-axis and y-axis ticks, then add labels and title (if needed).

We can copy and paste the code we wrote, then just change the parameters of the x-axis and y-axis as needed.

3.4.2 Chest Pain VS Heart Disease¶

We can see from this violin plot below, that a majority of the "no heart disease" observations have asymtopmatic pain. We also see a majority of the heart disease observations have their chest pain distributed around atypical angina. This makes sense, however you would also think there would be a large number of typical angina pain as well, which is surprising. But that may mean there are other factors at play here other than just chest pain that we may uncover further in our analysis

3.4.3 Maximum Heart Rate VS Heart Disease¶

We can see in this graph below that people who were not diagnosed with heart disease, their maximum heart rates are roughly normally distributed with a mean around 145. We also observe that people that were diagnosed with heart disease, had average heart rates of approximately 155 that look roughly distributed. Intuitively, we would expect higher maximum heart rates to be correlated with heart disease, because the heart is working faster and will wear itself out quicker leading to heart disease.

3.4.4 Age VS Heart Disease¶

The result below is extremely surprising. We see the average age of people not diagnosed with heart disease is higher than the average age of observations diagnosed with heart disease. We also see a wider range of ages for people diagnosed with heart disease including a lot more younger people in their early 40s. The result below is extremely counterintuitive. We may uncover why this is the case later in the analysis.

One possibility worth discussing is that there may be a kind of survivorship bias at play here and I think this is a plausible assumption. If your chest didn't hurt, and you were relatively young, would you go for an ECG? Probably not. However, if your chest did hurt, you probably would. We might be seeing a case like that happening here, where younger patients just aren't getting checked by their doctors for chest pain.

3.4.5 Sex VS Heart Disease¶

The results here are quite surprising. Men are twice more likely than women to have a heart attack according to Harvard. We see here that almost all the negative heart disease diagnoses were from men. Again, this might be some form survivorship bias where the men are going to get checked out before they have symptoms as a preventative measure, and the women aren't.

We do see in the people diagnosed with heart disease that the men slightly outweigh the women, and this is roughly consistently with medical literature on heart disease. However, we would expect to see about twice the number of men and we see only about 1 and 1/2 times the amount of men, but this doesn't raise any of our data science alarms or red flags.

3.4.6 Slope of peak exercise ST segment VS Heart Disease¶

The results here are consistent with what we would expect, but still a little off. We know during exercise a normal ST segment is flat or slopes downwards. A person with heart disease's segment will slope sharply upwards during exercise (a value of 2 in this case). We would expect there to be less flat ST segments for people diagnosed with heart diseases, but it isn't very significant

Part 4: Hypothesis testing and machine learning¶

4.1 Hypothesis Testing¶

Data scientists usually form a hypothesis about their data, then test it using statistical hypothesis testing (follow up article at link), and either reject or accept their hypothesis.

Based on our correlation matrix that showed chest pain and resting heart rate as the strongest correlated variable dependent variables, and our violin plot distributions, we will hypothesize that is a relationship between chest pain, resting heart rate, and heart disease diagnosis.

4.1.1 Statsmodels¶

Statsmodels (follow up article at link) is a statistics library written in Python and can quickly show us p-values and R-squared values. We will be using statsmodels ordinary least squares (follow up article at link) linear regression. Statsmodels does not do any cross validation, and is not a machine learning library, we will only be using it here for R-squared and p-values.

4.1.2 Step by Step Code-Walkthrough¶

Statmodels make it very easy for us, and we can do it in two lines of code. We broke it out into four lines of code declaring dependent and independent variables, respectively, just for ease of reading.

  1. declare independent and dependent variables
  2. invoke statsmodels ordinary least squares
  3. display the summary of the model

4.1.3 Chest Pain and Resting Heart Rate Linear Regression¶

It is quite feasible, using our intuition, that we anticipate a linear relationship between physiological measures and heart disease. Chest pain and resting heart rate would likely have a linear relationship to heart disease. The more your chest hurts the more likely something is probably wrong with your heart and the higher your resting heart rate the more likely there is something wrong with your heart.

We use statsmodels below to create a linear regression (without cross fold validation) and we see the R-squared (follow up article at link) value is .655 which means the model explains roughly 65.5% of the data.

We also see the p-value is 0.0 which means using a significance level of 0.05 we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is a relationship between chest pain, resting heart rate, and heart disease.

In [12]:
X = df[['cp', 'thalachh']]
y = df['output']
cp_thalachh_model = sm.OLS(y,X).fit()

4.1.4 Chest Pain and Resting Heart Rate Linear Regression Residuals¶

We can see the R-squared value is good, but we would expect there to be a stronger relationship. Let's explore the residuals of the model against age and sex (other parameter that appeared to influence the diagnoses of heart disease in our exploratory phase).

Note: Seaborn VS Matplotlib¶

Seaborn violin plots (follow up article at link) have an interesting way to show the distribution. Vhe actual violin shape that shows the distribution extends beyond the data's max and minimum points. You have to look at the box and whisker plot inside the violin to see the actual bounds. However, when we were plotting nonzeros values, and saw the violins going below zeros in part 3 that was quite confusing.

However, in part 4, we are plotting residual values (follow up article at link) which are an estimate of our linear regression models performance. Residuals are expected to sometimes be below 0, and that's okay. Seaborn makes it much easier to plot the residuals because we can skip the grouping phase we had to do in matplotlib which makes more cleaner and easier code. So we're going to jump into seaborn for this section. Which is good, because it gives the reader experience with both libraries!

4.1.5 Code walk through¶

The code below does the following:

  1. We use pandas cut to split age into equal bins
    1. Pandas cut takes a bins argument which we are passing a scalar value. The scalar value starts at the minimum age, goes to the maximum age+1 because pythons range() upper bound is exclusive, then the range of age divided by 4 because it works out to even bins of length of 12 years
  2. Seaborn makes it quite easy to plot residuals using bins, so we'll it here. Just one line of seaborn code, then some labels

4.1.6 Residuals of Chest Pain and Resting Heart Rate Linear Regression grouped by Age¶

We can clearly see from this model that age must be affecting the residuals. We know that residuals should be normally distributed around 0, but we don't see that here. We see that the young ages over estimated which means the model is suggesting that younger aged observations have heart disease when they don't. Additionally, we see that the model has negative residuals for older age groups, which means it is suggesting older observations do not have heart disease when they do. Clearly, age plays a big role in the model and we will need to take into consideration as we continue to iterate on our model. Intuitively, this makes sense, older people with older heart are more predisposed for heart disease.

Conclusion: We can see a linear relationship of the residuals, age needs to be taken into account when creating a model.

4.1.7 Residuals of Chest Pain and Resting Heart Rate Linear Regression grouped by Sex¶

Again, the residuals should be normally distributed around 0 but we don't see that. We can see below that the model is suggesting males have heart disease when they don't because the residual are positive. Additionally, we can see that the residuals for females is bimodal above and below 0, meaning the model both under and over estimates. When a distribution of residuals is bimodal, that means there is something more at play. However the bimodal distribution in the female group is not very significant, and I still think sex should be taken into account when creating a new model.

Conclusion: Female residuals is bimodal, and bimodal residuals is often an indicator that there is more at play than this variable is equipped to handle. For example, in this case, it is likely that there is more than just sex that explains heart disease. However, the bimodal distribution is not very significant in the female observations in this dataset and should probably still be taken into account when creating a new and hopefully more accurate model.

4.2 Machine Learning¶

As discussed briefly in the hypothesis testing, I think it is very plausible to assume that there is a linear relationship between physiological metrics and heart disease. Yes, we could employ more complex models like kmeans clustering, but I do not think it is necessary. We have seen good success as seen above, and this without doing any kind of cross-validation) (see link for article), because statsmodels is a closed model ordinary least squares algorithm that does not do any cross fold validation. Hopefully, once we do employ some machine learning and do some cross-validation, we will see our accuracy improve.

4.2.1 Linear Regression with sklearn¶

Sklearn, like statsmodels, uses a closed model ordinary least squares method which is based on scipy's Linear Regression. However, lets give it a try and see what we come up with! Sklearn is a little less intuitive than statsmodels, and that's why we've been avoiding it until this point. However, understanding how sklearn's linear regression works will be a good precursor to cross-validation in the subsequent section.

The result, is that it appears like sklearn actually does a better job of predicting residuals for ages 53-77, but the age groups 29-53 still appear to have poor residuals.

Step by Step Code-Walkthrough¶

  1. Drop na values to avoid the algorithm falsely predicting
  2. Create an array of input features
  3. Use numpy's vstack function to create a sequenced of arrays stacked vertically to use with sklearn
  4. Use numpy's transpose to reverse the axes of the array
  5. Use sklearn's Linear Regression, and fit it with our data
  6. Calculte the residuals of the linear model by hand
  7. Plot the residuals in seaborn, exactly how we did in the earlier sections
In [22]:
# For linear regression we will drop rows with NaN values, if they exist 
# (this is just a precautionary measure, we did this earlier)
data = df.dropna().copy()

# Isolate the features that will be used as predictors
input_features = [
    data['sex'],
    data['cp'],
    data['thalachh']
]
input_features = np.vstack(input_features)
input_features = input_features.transpose()

# Fit a model for predicting output
model = LinearRegression().fit(input_features, data['output'])


# Calculate the residual for each row in the dataframe
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    data.loc[index, "residual"] = row["output"] \
    - model.predict(np.array([
        data['sex'][index],
        data['cp'][index],
        data['thalachh'][index]
    ]).reshape(1, -1))

# Make a violin plot of mmse model residuals vs. SES
ax = sn.violinplot(x=data['age_bin'], y=data['residual'])
ax.set_title('Residuals grouped by Age')
plt.show()

4.2.1 Kfolds Cross-Validation Linear Regression with sklearn¶

Now, let's do some real machine learning. cross-validation) (see link for article) is a popular machine learning technique that splits your dataset into a training dataset and a testing dataset. You train your machine learning model with the training set, then use the testing dataset to verify the predictions.

Kfolds splits data into multiple cross-validation sets and trains/tests with multiple segments of the data and results in a more robuts model. Lets use them in combination below.

Step by Step Code-Walkthrough¶

  1. We will create a new dataframe with the data just for ease of use (we have a lot of residual columsn, age_bins, etc.)
  2. split into train and test data
  3. use kfolds to create a cross-validation scheme
  4. specify the range of hypermaraters we will let the model tune
  5. gather the input features for the model
  6. use numpy to stack and transpose the parameters
  7. fit our training data with out linear regression
  8. feed our model into the sklearn recursive feature elimination algorithm
  9. use grid search CV to optimize our parameters and fit the model
  10. calculate residuals and graph using seaborn
In [23]:
# create fresh data frame with existing residuals
data = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PerryProjects/DataScienceTutorial/main/heart.csv')

# train / test split for cross_validation
df_train, df_test = train_test_split(data, 
                                     train_size = 0.7, 
                                     test_size = 0.3, 
                                     random_state = 100)

# create independent and dependent variables
y_train = data.pop('output') 
X_train = data
# create a cross-validation scheme
folds = KFold(n_splits = 5, shuffle = True, random_state = 100)

# specify range of hyperparameters to tune
hyper_params = [{'n_features_to_select': list(range(1, 13))}]

# gather input features
input_features = [
    df_train['sex'],
    df_train['cp'],
    df_train['thalachh'],
    df_train['trtbps'],
    df_train['chol'],
    df_train['fbs'],
    df_train['restecg'],
    df_train['thalachh'],
    df_train['exng'],
    df_train['oldpeak'],
    df_train['slp'],
    df_train['caa'],
    df_train['thall'],
]
input_features = np.vstack(input_features)
input_features = input_features.transpose()

# create linear regression
lm = LinearRegression().fit(input_features, df_train['output'])
lm.fit(X_train, y_train)
# recursive feature elimination
rfe = RFE(lm).fit(input_features, df_train['output'])

# # 3.2 call GridSearchCV()
model_cv = GridSearchCV(estimator = rfe, 
                        param_grid = hyper_params, 
                        scoring= 'r2', 
                        cv = folds, 
                        verbose = 1,
                        return_train_score=True)      

# fit the model
model_cv.fit(input_features, df_train['output'])

# Calculate the residual for each row in the dataframe
for index, row in df_train.iterrows():
    data.loc[index, "residual"] = row["output"] \
    - model_cv.predict(np.array([
            data['sex'][index],
            data['cp'][index],
            data['thalachh'][index],
            data['trtbps'][index],
            data['chol'][index],
            data['fbs'][index],
            data['restecg'][index],
            data['thalachh'][index],
            data['exng'][index],
            data['oldpeak'][index],
            data['slp'][index],
            data['caa'][index],
            data['thall'][index],
        ]).reshape(1, -1))
    
# Create equal sized age bins
age_min = df_train['age'].min()
age_max = df_train['age'].max()
data['age_bin'] = pd.cut(data['age'],bins=range(age_min,age_max+1,(age_max-age_min)//4))

# Make a violin plot of residuals VS age
ax = sn.violinplot(x=data['age_bin'], y=data['residual'])
ax.set_title('Residuals grouped by Age')
plt.show()

Fitting 5 folds for each of 12 candidates, totalling 60 fits

4.2.1 ML Results¶

We can see from our model's residuals above, that after we utilized cross-validation kfolds we have slightly improved our residuals across the board. Specifically, the tail of 29-41 is shorter, the 53-65 age group's distribution is more closely centered 0, and the 65-77 age group's upper and lower bounds and closer to 0 and the distribution is much more closely centered on 0.

However, they are not very significantly improved over the normal linear regression without cross-validation, only slightly!

Part 5: Communication of insights attained¶

We learned quite a bit about the entire data science pipeline, pandas, sklearn, statsmodels, seaborn, and matplotlib. We also picked up quite a bit of domain knowledge about heart disease.

Overall, we have demonstrated that predicting heart disease is very possible. The accuracy we demonstrated points towards the fact that with a richer dataset and more refinement of our models/approaches we can definitely predict heart disease with good accuracy.

We saw some outliers in this dataset that went against the literature. We observed in this dataset that males are not more than double likely than females to have heart disease. We also saw that young people are also quite at risk for heart disease as well, and that age is not a good predictor of heart disease. We also saw that there more older people WITHOUT heart disease than with heart disease, this is a very shocking finding. I would be very curious to see if this holds true across datasets.

Further work would need to be done to verify the assumptions we had in this dataset, like the fact we observed that the average age of a person WITHOUT heart disease was older than the average age of a person WITH heart disease. As stated earlier, this could be a survivorship bias at play, that younger people who feel healthy are not going to the doctor to get their hearts checked. Only young people with heart issues are going to get checked out, and therefore only younger people with heart issues will have their data points recorded, while younger people who do not have heart issues will not have their data recorded and thus it falsely appears older people have healthier hearts because older people go to get checked out more often even without chest pain / heart issues.

We also saw that it looks like chest pain, maximum heart rate, and sex are the strongest predictors and parameters that should be used in a model to predict heart disease; we also saw that (at least with this data) that age, cholesterol, ECG results, and fasting blood sugar are not great predictors of heart disease.

Further work needs to be done to find more datasets and verify if these findings we have discovered here hold true across multiple datasets on heart disease. We also could work on refining our models and our machine learning approaches too.

Please checkout all of the hyperlinks in this article for further reading resources to continue learning, and good luck!¶
